WEBVTT

00:02.600 --> 00:04.478
ANNOUNCER:
<i>In last week's episode of</i> Soap,

00:04.680 --> 00:08.833
<i>a surprised Corinne was booked</i>
<i>for the murder of Peter Campbell.</i>

00:09.040 --> 00:12.158
<i>But this is nothing compared</i>
<i>to the surprise in store for her</i>

00:12.360 --> 00:15.990
<i>when she finds out</i>
<i>that a Swedish lady,</i>
<i>Ingrid Svenson,</i>

00:16.200 --> 00:19.671
<i>has come from Ecuador</i>
<i>to pay Corinne a surprise visit,</i>

00:20.040 --> 00:23.192
<i>and has shown a surprised</i>
<i>Chief Tinkler proof</i>

00:23.400 --> 00:25.915
<i>that she is Corinne's real mother.</i>

00:26.160 --> 00:30.598
<i>Surprised? You won't be</i>
<i>after this week's episode of</i> Soap.

00:30.800 --> 00:32.677
[♪♪♪]

00:35.560 --> 00:38.439
<i>This is the story of two sisters:</i>

00:38.640 --> 00:41.838
<i>Jessica Tate and Mary Campbell.</i>

00:42.720 --> 00:45.076
<i>These are the Tates.</i>

00:45.880 --> 00:48.634
<i>And these are the Campbells.</i>

00:49.680 --> 00:52.115
<i>And this is</i> Soap.

00:52.320 --> 00:54.437
[♪♪♪]

00:55.080 --> 00:58.152
You...
Get off me.

00:58.360 --> 01:02.149
Stop it. Boys, boys.
Get off me.

01:02.360 --> 01:04.477
[ALL CHATTERING]

01:06.240 --> 01:08.516
[♪♪♪]

01:10.000 --> 01:16.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:22.400 --> 01:25.234
Oh, Ma. Daddy.
Oh, baby.

01:25.440 --> 01:27.875
Baby, the bail will be here any minute.
Oh, good.

01:28.120 --> 01:32.160
I cannot believe
these accommodations.

01:32.360 --> 01:33.555
Well, I mean, Chester,

01:33.760 --> 01:37.834
no wonder people are
always trying to break
out of places like this.

01:38.040 --> 01:39.040
[GASPS]

01:39.200 --> 01:41.874
Chester, look at that.

01:42.840 --> 01:45.639
Would you look at that?
I see it, Jessica.

01:45.840 --> 01:47.957
It's a toilet.

01:49.040 --> 01:52.078
I know what it is.
It's right in the middle of the room.

01:52.280 --> 01:54.749
How do they expect
anybody to use that?

01:54.960 --> 01:59.079
Jessica, if you're
serving a 10-year sentence,
eventually you'll have to.

02:01.040 --> 02:03.999
Look at this.
You poor child.

02:04.200 --> 02:07.272
Shut up in this cell
without any sunshine,

02:07.480 --> 02:09.312
hundreds of feet
below the earth.

02:10.160 --> 02:12.994
The chains of prisoners
clanking in the night.

02:13.680 --> 02:16.434
The musty smell
of the wet stones

02:16.640 --> 02:20.077
and the sound of scampering rats
across the floor at night.

02:20.280 --> 02:21.714
Jessica.
Huh?

02:21.920 --> 02:25.880
Corinne is in a Connecticut jail.
She's not the prisoner of Zenda.

02:26.880 --> 02:29.475
Corinne, I have
a surprise for you.

02:29.680 --> 02:31.353
Bail?
No, better.

02:31.560 --> 02:34.871
Corinne, Corinne, Corinne.

02:35.080 --> 02:38.869
Oh, my God.
Who is this?

02:39.080 --> 02:44.155
Corinne, Corinne, Corinne.
Who is this?

02:44.840 --> 02:46.672
Who are you?
Who am I?

02:46.880 --> 02:48.109
Yes, who are you?

02:48.360 --> 02:49.396
Ha!

02:49.600 --> 02:50.875
Who is this?

02:51.080 --> 02:56.553
Twenty-three years.
For 23 years,
I've been in Ecuador.

02:56.760 --> 03:00.674
And for 23 years,
I've hated you.

03:00.880 --> 03:02.837
Jessica, who is this person?

03:03.040 --> 03:06.272
Look at her. Look at
what you've done.

03:06.480 --> 03:09.518
It wasn't bad enough
you took her away from me,

03:09.720 --> 03:13.430
but look at how you
brought her up, to be in jail.

03:14.120 --> 03:16.919
Oh, my God, it's her.

03:17.720 --> 03:22.317
Right. Thought you'd never
see me again, did you? Ha!

03:24.360 --> 03:30.516
Mother, who is this woman?
Darling, I am your mother.

03:31.720 --> 03:33.552
Oh.

03:35.160 --> 03:37.800
Sheriff, get her out of here.
She's nuts.

03:38.000 --> 03:41.311
She's got documents,
and she certainly
knows your name.

03:41.520 --> 03:44.831
She says she's my mother.
She's not my mother.

03:45.040 --> 03:48.636
This is my mother.
Mother?

03:49.600 --> 03:52.160
Mother, for God's sake,
tell me who this is.

03:52.480 --> 03:55.154
Uh, Corinne,
this is Ingrid Svenson.

03:55.360 --> 03:56.794
Ingrid, this is Corinne.

03:57.000 --> 04:00.072
Corinne, Corinne, Corinne.

04:01.680 --> 04:05.037
She says she's my mother.
Yes, she did say that, didn't she?

04:05.240 --> 04:07.357
Well, who is she?
She is your mother.

04:07.560 --> 04:09.199
Who's my mother?
She's your mother.

04:09.400 --> 04:10.959
Which she?
That she.

04:11.160 --> 04:13.436
This she?
That she.

04:15.000 --> 04:18.880
Ingrid's my mother?
Yes, it's a long story, Corinne.

04:19.079 --> 04:22.039
Corinne, Corinne, Corinne.

04:27.720 --> 04:30.030
Why didn't you tell me?

04:30.800 --> 04:35.317
You never told me.
How could you not tell me?

04:35.520 --> 04:40.800
Well, we thought you'd never know.
I want you to go now.

04:41.000 --> 04:42.753
Corinne, we were trying
to protect you.

04:42.960 --> 04:46.795
I said, go.
Corinne, I love you.

04:47.320 --> 04:51.473
She wants you to go.
Does she have to spit
at you?

04:53.360 --> 04:59.197
Corinne, if you had been
our own child, we couldn't
have loved you any more.

04:59.400 --> 05:03.474
Sheriff, get them out of here.
Okay. It's time. Let's go.

05:03.680 --> 05:05.881
Come on, come on, come on.
Let's go. Let's go. Let's go.

05:05.960 --> 05:07.314
Ha!

05:08.880 --> 05:12.396
My little girl.

05:12.600 --> 05:15.513
Don't worry,
we'll get you out of here.

05:15.720 --> 05:19.634
I hired a detective,
and we get you out of here.

05:19.840 --> 05:22.400
And then we get a place together

05:22.600 --> 05:26.071
and get to know each other
all over again.

05:26.280 --> 05:30.991
Now, let Mother look
at how pretty you are.

05:32.120 --> 05:34.715
So, now, tell Mother,

05:34.920 --> 05:38.516
what have you been doing
the last 23 years?

05:40.160 --> 05:42.117
[♪♪♪]

05:44.680 --> 05:46.080
I said, quiet, Bob.

05:46.280 --> 05:49.318
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
You be quiet.
I'm happy for a change.

05:52.040 --> 05:54.680
Burt, what in the world is that?

05:54.880 --> 05:57.190
Peter's bathtub.
I got the rest outside.

05:57.400 --> 06:00.632
Boy, I've heard of souvenirs,
but that's ridiculous.

06:00.840 --> 06:02.957
Burt, what are you doing
with Peter's bathtub?

06:03.160 --> 06:05.880
Why not? Peter doesn't
need it anymore.

06:06.120 --> 06:08.794
In this tub is the answer.
I know it. It's here. It's here.

06:09.280 --> 06:11.590
The murderer left his trace
right in there.

06:11.800 --> 06:13.678
Or out there with
one of the other pieces.

06:13.880 --> 06:15.917
I thought you said
Corinne did it.

06:16.240 --> 06:17.833
[CHUCKLES]

06:18.040 --> 06:19.759
Not necessarily.

06:19.960 --> 06:21.155
Hey, everybody.

06:21.360 --> 06:24.592
Hey, listen, there's this huge chunk
of bathtub laying out in the path.

06:24.800 --> 06:26.240
Somebody could
kill themselves on it.

06:26.320 --> 06:28.676
Yeah, somebody already did.

06:30.800 --> 06:33.190
Danny, where's your disguise?

06:33.400 --> 06:35.517
Well, I don't think I'm
gonna need it anymore.

06:35.720 --> 06:37.321
I found somebody
who's gonna help me out.

06:37.360 --> 06:38.953
Ah. Too bad.

06:39.160 --> 06:40.514
[DOORBELL RINGS]

06:43.320 --> 06:44.515
Mrs. Campbell?
Yes?

06:44.720 --> 06:47.519
I am Heinrich Himmel,

06:48.040 --> 06:52.193
a private investigator
hired by Corinne Tate's mother.

06:52.400 --> 06:54.278
May I come in?

06:55.480 --> 06:57.233
Yes.
I think you should know

06:57.440 --> 07:01.229
that there is a broken
bathtub on your lawn,
and it looks disgusting.

07:01.440 --> 07:03.079
Well, that's mine. I'll get it.
Halt!

07:05.800 --> 07:08.235
I didn't know Jessica
had hired a private detective.

07:08.440 --> 07:09.669
She didn't.
But you said...

07:09.880 --> 07:13.556
I said, Corinne Tate's mother.
Ingrid Svenson.

07:14.280 --> 07:16.636
Ingrid Svenson?

07:16.880 --> 07:18.633
Ingrid Svenson.

07:18.840 --> 07:21.196
BOB: Who's Ingrid Svenson?
Who's Ingrid Svenson?

07:21.400 --> 07:23.073
Quiet!

07:23.920 --> 07:26.560
Enough with this
"Ingrid Svenson."
Now, Mrs. Campbell,

07:26.760 --> 07:29.559
I have questions
and you will give answers.

07:29.760 --> 07:32.594
Make them brief,
no long, boring stories,

07:32.800 --> 07:35.520
which you Americans
seem so bent on telling.

07:35.720 --> 07:37.996
Who is this Ingrid Svenson?
What did I say?!

07:39.400 --> 07:41.596
What did you just hear me say?!

07:44.560 --> 07:45.755
I'll tell you later.

07:45.960 --> 07:49.590
Tell them now. They'll never shut up
if you don't tell them now, but quick.

07:49.800 --> 07:52.918
A quick, short story.
No details. Understand?
No details.

07:53.120 --> 07:54.120
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

07:54.280 --> 07:56.078
Sit. Sit. Sit.

07:58.880 --> 08:02.635
Well, Jessica and I
had a brother, Randolph.

08:02.840 --> 08:04.559
You never told me
you had a brother.

08:04.760 --> 08:06.160
Shut up.
She's telling you now.

08:07.160 --> 08:09.311
Well, Randolph was
kind of peculiar...

08:09.520 --> 08:10.520
Detail.

08:10.720 --> 08:13.997
What?
That is a detail. "Peculiar" is a detail.

08:14.800 --> 08:20.273
Uh, well, Randolph
took a liking to Ingrid,
our Swedish maid.

08:20.480 --> 08:24.190
See, Ingrid didn't speak any
English, so she didn't know
Randolph was peculiar.

08:24.400 --> 08:26.392
Details. Those are details.

08:26.600 --> 08:31.072
We don't care about "peculiar."
You are all peculiar.

08:31.600 --> 08:35.753
Anyway, Ingrid got pregnant
and had Corinne.

08:35.960 --> 08:39.397
Now, Mother wanted
the baby, so she very
cleverly offered to babysit.

08:39.600 --> 08:42.068
And then she sent Ingrid
and Randolph to Ecuador...

08:42.280 --> 08:44.875
Details, more details.
Hup, hup, hup!

08:45.080 --> 08:47.754
She told the authorities
that Ingrid was an illegal alien,

08:47.960 --> 08:51.920
and that Randolph was seeking
to overthrow the government.
So they had to stay in Ecuador,

08:52.120 --> 08:54.476
and Mother gave
Jessica the baby to
be raised as a Tate.

08:54.680 --> 08:57.070
But why didn't they...?
No questions!

08:57.920 --> 08:59.400
That's it. Finished.

08:59.600 --> 09:02.434
I don't want to hear another word
about this idiotic business.

09:02.640 --> 09:07.396
Now, Mr. Campbell,
I understand that recently
you consulted a psychiatrist.

09:07.600 --> 09:11.116
Did you consult him because
of your propensity for violence?

09:11.560 --> 09:13.040
That's none of your business.

09:13.240 --> 09:15.197
You are wrong,
Mr. Campbell Dummkopf.

09:16.600 --> 09:19.911
It is very much my business.
Now, if you won't tell me why
you saw him,

09:20.120 --> 09:24.990
I will have to assume
it was for help in controlling
your violent tendencies.

09:25.200 --> 09:28.876
Well, it was not, you see.
It was because I...

09:30.920 --> 09:33.799
Okay, violence.

09:34.000 --> 09:35.000
Impotence.

09:36.600 --> 09:38.319
Really?
Yeah.

09:38.520 --> 09:40.239
No kidding.
No, it's the truth.

09:40.480 --> 09:41.914
[LAUGHING]

09:43.240 --> 09:44.993
I love it.

09:46.000 --> 09:48.595
So classically American.

09:48.800 --> 09:51.076
A problem we never
have in Germany.

09:51.280 --> 09:52.760
No impotence, no smog...

09:52.960 --> 09:55.520
No Jews.
No...

09:58.320 --> 10:02.917
Impotence?
A big, robust guy like you?

10:06.000 --> 10:09.835
I just wish I had a camera
for that one, Mr. Campbell.

10:10.040 --> 10:13.238
I could put you in jail
and throw away the key.

10:13.720 --> 10:15.154
Now, then, Mrs. Campbell,

10:15.360 --> 10:18.398
how much did you resent,
hate and despise Peter Campbell?

10:18.600 --> 10:21.718
What?
Just answer, please, the question.

10:21.920 --> 10:25.914
Good God. You people stall
like nobody's business.

10:26.160 --> 10:28.550
I didn't hate him.
I never hated him.

10:28.760 --> 10:32.390
Okay. Fine.
We have here denial, then.

10:32.640 --> 10:35.075
Denial of the painful truth.

10:35.680 --> 10:36.680
Now, Jodie...

10:36.880 --> 10:39.634
That's not true.
I said, Jodie!

10:39.840 --> 10:41.991
Are you Jodie?

10:42.200 --> 10:44.920
Do you look like Jodie?
Do you talk like Jodie?

10:45.120 --> 10:46.679
Sometimes they dress alike.

10:50.800 --> 10:52.792
Please to put the toy away.

10:53.320 --> 10:54.436
Who is he talking to?

10:54.640 --> 10:55.761
[IN NORMAL VOICE] Just wait.

10:55.800 --> 10:59.191
Now, Jodie, in your case it was
obviously a transference, hm?

10:59.400 --> 11:01.995
A homosexual in love
with an athlete,

11:02.200 --> 11:03.200
who spurned him.

11:03.360 --> 11:06.717
Thus turning to rage
and then... murder.

11:08.160 --> 11:11.312
We have precedents for this
type of homosexual behaviour.

11:11.520 --> 11:16.720
Not in Germany, of course.
We have no homosexuals
in Germany.

11:16.920 --> 11:19.276
They are in Austria.

11:21.360 --> 11:22.589
Or Switzerland.

11:22.800 --> 11:24.951
Where in Switzerland?

11:27.640 --> 11:29.677
Now, Danny, this is an easy one.

11:29.880 --> 11:32.634
You work in
a violent society, hm?

11:32.840 --> 11:35.355
You would think nothing
of killing Peter, hm?

11:36.120 --> 11:37.474
No.

11:37.680 --> 11:41.674
And you, we know you
always hated your brother.

11:41.880 --> 11:44.076
I did not.
Because you were jealous of him.

11:44.280 --> 11:47.557
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
Oh, go back to Argentina, Adolf.

11:49.040 --> 11:52.670
He was an athlete,
and you, Chuck?
You're a klutz.

11:52.880 --> 11:56.920
He had many women.
You? You got yourself
a hunk of bark.

11:57.600 --> 11:58.795
Now, listen...

12:05.600 --> 12:07.751
So you killed him.
He did not.

12:07.960 --> 12:10.350
Because he reminded you
of what you weren't...

12:10.560 --> 12:12.074
He didn't do it,
he didn't do it.

12:12.280 --> 12:15.159
Of what you aren't,
of what you could never be.

12:15.360 --> 12:17.591
Hey, who do you think...?
Shut up!

12:20.160 --> 12:22.834
I don't want to hear
another word from you.

12:24.920 --> 12:28.231
This stupidity
has wasted my time.

12:31.760 --> 12:35.310
I will file my report.
You will all stay in town.

12:35.520 --> 12:40.993
I hope I never again have
to see any of you as long
as I live, hm? Goodbye.

12:44.080 --> 12:47.312
Nice, warm guy.
I like him.

12:47.560 --> 12:49.517
[♪♪♪]

12:55.680 --> 12:57.637
[♪♪♪]

12:59.160 --> 13:01.834
So it's all my fault,
Mary. All of it.

13:02.040 --> 13:05.920
Peter's death, Corinne's arrest,
Ingrid's arrival, it's all my fault.

13:06.120 --> 13:09.158
Jessica, don't be silly. None of that
has anything to do with you.

13:09.360 --> 13:12.751
No? Wherever I am, Mary,
there's death and destruction.

13:12.960 --> 13:15.839
It's always been that way.
Jessica, that's not true.

13:16.040 --> 13:18.555
You remember Mr. Rolo
and what happened to him?

13:18.800 --> 13:20.757
Mr. Rolo?
Yes, you remember.

13:20.960 --> 13:24.240
The clown that used to
entertain at all of our birthday
parties when we were little.

13:24.720 --> 13:27.679
Mr. Rolo.

13:28.400 --> 13:31.234
Oh, Jessica, do you
remember Mr. Rolo?

13:31.440 --> 13:35.229
Well, Mary, obviously I do,
I just brought him up.

13:35.720 --> 13:38.315
I loved Mr. Rolo.

13:38.560 --> 13:40.517
And you remember
how at my birthday party,

13:40.720 --> 13:43.315
he just keeled over
and dropped dead on the spot?

13:45.280 --> 13:48.990
If I am not the kiss of death, Mary,
I don't know who is.

13:49.200 --> 13:50.793
Jessie, he was a sick man.

13:51.000 --> 13:54.118
At my birthday party,
right in the middle of
his rabbit trick,

13:54.320 --> 13:58.280
he just turned blue and sunk
to the floor, dead as a doornail.

13:58.480 --> 14:02.554
The man had high blood pressure,
he weighed nearly 300 pounds.

14:02.760 --> 14:05.036
As if that wasn't enough,
his dying,

14:05.240 --> 14:08.870
I mean, when he dropped dead
he fell on the rabbit and killed him.

14:10.680 --> 14:11.830
He did?

14:12.080 --> 14:14.720
Of course.
Don't you remember, Mary?

14:14.920 --> 14:17.560
When they were trying
to revive him, all you could see

14:17.760 --> 14:21.993
were those two little
white ears sticking out
from under his stomach.

14:22.240 --> 14:27.190
Mr. Rolo and the rabbit died
at my birthday party.

14:27.400 --> 14:29.437
Mary, I am the kiss of death.

14:29.640 --> 14:31.233
[GUNSHOTS]

14:31.440 --> 14:35.354
Mary, I think a car just
backfired in your basement.

14:35.560 --> 14:37.597
No, it's Burt.

14:37.800 --> 14:41.794
Well, if that is Burt, Mary,
I think you're probably a widow.

14:42.000 --> 14:43.593
Those were shots.

14:43.800 --> 14:47.680
No, he's just doing
some ballistics tests.

14:47.880 --> 14:49.792
He's trying to find
the murderer.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.277
Well, Mary, if the murderer
ever was in your basement,

14:53.480 --> 14:56.393
I feel sure he would
have left by now.

14:57.120 --> 15:00.796
Burt's acting
a little strange lately.

15:01.040 --> 15:04.317
Oh, Mary, Burt's always
been slightly strange.

15:04.560 --> 15:09.760
No, no, it's more than that.
He's acting kind of, uh, crazy.

15:09.960 --> 15:12.998
Oh, I don't think you have
anything to worry about Mary.

15:13.200 --> 15:16.159
I mean, we both know Burt's
always been a little strange.

15:16.360 --> 15:18.591
That's what makes him
so adorable.

15:18.800 --> 15:22.271
I mean, he's just a sweet man
with a slightly jumpy personality,

15:22.480 --> 15:24.119
but I mean, he's not crazy.

15:27.440 --> 15:30.512
Hi, Mare.
Hello, darling.

15:30.760 --> 15:33.594
Hi, Jess.
Hi, Burt.

15:38.760 --> 15:40.035
Oh, Burt!
What?

15:40.240 --> 15:41.993
What are you doing?
Nothing.

15:42.200 --> 15:46.353
Burt, you just pulled
a hair out from my head.

15:46.560 --> 15:48.199
No, I didn't.

15:53.080 --> 15:55.549
I'm not finished.

15:56.120 --> 15:58.589
That your spoon?
Yes.

16:00.520 --> 16:03.274
Perhaps he'd like some tea.

16:04.560 --> 16:07.917
My goodness! What are you doing?
Nothing.

16:08.120 --> 16:10.112
Burt, you pulled a hair
out of my head.

16:10.320 --> 16:13.154
And I just saw you pull one
out of Jessica's head.

16:13.360 --> 16:15.431
More than one, I'm afraid.

16:15.680 --> 16:19.230
Well, you see, I'm just conducting
a test, Mary. Conducting a test.

16:19.440 --> 16:22.956
You see, I found a hair
in Peter's bathtub.

16:23.200 --> 16:26.557
A hair in his tub.

16:26.800 --> 16:29.918
Well, of course, of course,
it's a bathtub.

16:30.120 --> 16:32.510
There are always hairs
in the bathtub.

16:32.720 --> 16:35.360
It's such a problem. Hair.

16:35.560 --> 16:39.873
Oh, it just clogs up the drain,
and then the plumber has to
come and remove it.

16:40.080 --> 16:43.790
Have you ever seen
what they remove, Burt?
Oh, it's so disgusting.

16:46.040 --> 16:47.793
It's no wonder
they charge so much.

16:48.000 --> 16:53.075
I'd charge a fortune too,
if I had to look at hairy
hunks of gloop all day.

16:53.800 --> 16:54.870
"Gloop."

16:55.080 --> 16:57.117
[ALL CHUCKLING]

16:57.320 --> 16:59.073
"Gloop."

17:01.240 --> 17:07.191
Well, it just might be a hairy hunk
of gloop that hangs one of you.

17:13.240 --> 17:16.199
[♪♪♪]

17:22.319 --> 17:25.950
Chester, I just realised
something very important.

17:26.400 --> 17:27.400
What, Jessica?

17:27.560 --> 17:28.994
[DOORBELL RINGS]

17:30.960 --> 17:33.077
You want me to get that?

17:37.320 --> 17:38.390
Would you mind?

17:45.320 --> 17:47.357
What did you realise, Jessica?

17:47.560 --> 17:50.120
Ten years ago,
this could never have happened.

17:50.720 --> 17:53.918
What?
Peter was a tennis teacher.

17:54.120 --> 17:57.352
Yes.
Ten years ago, nobody played tennis.

17:57.560 --> 18:02.112
The recent popularity of tennis
has ruined our lives.

18:02.720 --> 18:06.600
He always comes at meal times.
The guy's a raccoon.

18:07.800 --> 18:11.430
I'm sorry to bother you.
Tinkler, what do you want?

18:11.640 --> 18:14.599
Well, first I'd like to introduce
Investigator Rick Himmel.

18:14.800 --> 18:17.031
Not Rick, you fool.
Heinrich. Heinrich!

18:17.240 --> 18:19.550
Are you a foreigner?

18:22.400 --> 18:23.400
He's German.

18:23.760 --> 18:25.752
German?

18:31.840 --> 18:36.357
Good work, corporal.
Capturing them isn't easy.

18:37.160 --> 18:38.196
Carry on.

18:42.280 --> 18:47.560
Tinkler, do you want something,
or is this a Lufthansa tour?

18:47.760 --> 18:49.911
[LAUGHING]

18:50.520 --> 18:52.989
Well, I would like to
look through the house.

18:53.200 --> 18:55.760
What? I've had
enough, Tinkler.

18:55.960 --> 18:58.350
I've had enough of you.
This is my house.

18:58.560 --> 19:02.793
Get out of here, once and for all,
before I call the police.

19:06.200 --> 19:07.429
I am the police.

19:07.640 --> 19:09.836
As difficult as
that is to believe.

19:10.040 --> 19:13.590
I have a search warrant.
And while I am looking
through your house,

19:13.800 --> 19:15.712
Rick here has some
questions he wants to ask.

19:15.920 --> 19:18.594
Heinrich! Heinrich, you fool.

19:18.800 --> 19:21.269
Now, you are Eunice, I presume?

19:21.480 --> 19:22.755
Mm-hm.

19:22.960 --> 19:24.440
You like to fool people,
don't you?

19:24.640 --> 19:25.640
What do you mean?

19:25.840 --> 19:29.277
Oh, pretending to be cold,
that you don't go out.

19:29.480 --> 19:31.517
When we both know
that you're involved with...

19:31.720 --> 19:33.757
Oh, please.

19:34.960 --> 19:39.159
Fortunately for you,
you are a fooler,
not a murderer.

19:39.360 --> 19:41.795
Do you find it difficult
talking with a German accent?

19:44.760 --> 19:48.470
Because it seems like it
would be exhausting the way
you pronounce words so hard.

19:48.680 --> 19:52.310
I mean, sometimes you even
spit a little when you talk.

19:53.000 --> 19:54.753
Talk? Talk?

19:54.960 --> 19:58.271
They can put matches
under my nails, I'll never talk.

19:58.480 --> 19:59.709
So never talk!

19:59.920 --> 20:02.435
I don't care about
your talking. Never talk.

20:02.920 --> 20:05.037
I won't.

20:06.280 --> 20:08.511
Good, don't.

20:08.720 --> 20:10.951
I won't.

20:11.640 --> 20:15.998
I swear, I don't know how
you people won the war.

20:17.400 --> 20:22.634
I never saw such a nation
of utter fools, except in Italy.

20:24.920 --> 20:29.551
But they, of course, can cook.
You people, you can't even do that.

20:29.760 --> 20:32.400
There. There you did it.
When you said "that,"
you spit a little.

20:32.600 --> 20:36.480
You did. I felt it
on my cheek.

20:39.560 --> 20:43.474
And you, oh,
you are my favourite, hm?

20:43.680 --> 20:44.680
[CHUCKLES]

20:44.880 --> 20:50.353
Boy, oh, boy, I gotta hand it
to you. You are something.

20:50.560 --> 20:52.313
Boy, are you a busy guy.

20:54.280 --> 20:57.318
There's that pigeon, huh?
And then that secretary.

20:57.520 --> 20:59.193
I admire you.

20:59.400 --> 21:02.871
If you committed the murder,
you should get away with it.

21:05.200 --> 21:06.793
Thank you.

21:07.480 --> 21:08.994
You.

21:09.440 --> 21:11.830
You are the black
servant, Benson.

21:12.400 --> 21:15.871
No, I am Japanese
houseboy, Mojo.

21:17.960 --> 21:19.280
Halt!

21:21.200 --> 21:24.557
You could have killed Peter, hm?

21:24.760 --> 21:27.639
Because you were jealous.

21:28.280 --> 21:33.753
He was white. You are black.
He had women, youth, freedom.

21:33.960 --> 21:37.715
You? You've got an apron
and maybe a decent timestep.

21:39.960 --> 21:44.159
Now, let me tell you something,
you little Nazi shrimp.

21:44.960 --> 21:47.270
Now, you can talk to them
any way you want to,

21:47.480 --> 21:49.631
but now you're
talking to me, Benson,

21:49.840 --> 21:54.517
and I personally have
had it with your shouting
and bullying and spitting.

21:54.720 --> 21:59.351
Nobody here killed
anyone, not yet.

22:01.280 --> 22:03.033
Bravo, Benson.

22:07.320 --> 22:11.314
Sorry about that, folks.
There will be no dessert tonight.

22:12.480 --> 22:16.360
Well, folks, I've got some
good news and some bad news.

22:20.640 --> 22:23.712
Is that strawberry shortcake?
Yes.

22:23.920 --> 22:26.674
Oh, boy, do I love
strawberry shortcake.

22:26.880 --> 22:28.314
Tinkler?
Oh, yeah.

22:28.560 --> 22:31.120
Well, the charges against
Corinne have been dropped.
That's the good news.

22:31.320 --> 22:33.880
Oh, Chester, isn't it wonderful?

22:35.040 --> 22:36.520
Now for the bad news.

22:36.720 --> 22:38.598
Couldn't we just
forget about that?

22:38.800 --> 22:41.315
On my little search
through your house,

22:41.520 --> 22:43.716
I found the gun that
shot Peter Campbell.

22:44.240 --> 22:46.596
I found the knife that
stabbed Peter Campbell.

22:47.560 --> 22:51.395
And I found the brick
that hit Peter Campbell.

22:52.680 --> 22:54.512
Now, the gun was found
in your drawer.

22:54.720 --> 22:56.871
The knife was found
in your jewellery box.

22:57.080 --> 22:59.037
And the brick was found
in your rose garden.

22:59.240 --> 23:03.519
Mrs. Tate, you are under arrest
for the murder of Peter Campbell.

23:04.040 --> 23:05.918
[♪♪♪]

23:13.120 --> 23:15.430
